The coefficient on distance is negative (further → cheaper), stars is positive (higher rated → more expensive). But should we trust the functional form? The first diagnostic is the **residuals-vs-fitted plot**.

## Building the residuals-vs-fitted plot

`broom::augment()` adds fitted values (`.fitted`) and residuals (`.resid`) to the original data frame. That is all we need:


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
augment(model_ext) |>
  ggplot(aes(.fitted, .resid)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.12, color = "steelblue", size = 0.7) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed", color = "gray50") +
  geom_smooth(method = "loess", se = FALSE, color = "tomato", linewidth = 1) +
  labs(x = "Fitted values (€)", y = "Residuals (€)",
       title = "Level-level: price ~ distance + stars",
       subtitle = "The smoother should be flat — it is not") +
  theme_minimal()
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![Residuals vs. fitted values for the level-level model. The red smoother curves upward — the functional form is misspecified.](demo_files/figure-html/fig-resid-base-1.png){#fig-resid-base width=672}
:::
:::


The upward curve at high fitted values tells us the model systematically underpredicts expensive hotels. The relationship is not linear in levels.

## Comparing specifications


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
make_resid <- function(m, title) {
  augment(m) |>
    ggplot(aes(.fitted, .resid)) +
    geom_point(alpha = 0.12, color = "steelblue", size = 0.7) +
    geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed", color = "gray50") +
    geom_smooth(method = "loess", se = FALSE, color = "tomato", linewidth = 0.9) +
    labs(x = "Fitted values", y = "Residuals", title = title) +
    theme_minimal(base_size = 11)
}

m_quad <- lm(price ~ distance + I(distance^2) + stars, data = hotels)

make_resid(model_ext,  "Level-level") +
make_resid(m_quad,     "Quadratic") +
make_resid(model_work, "Log-log")
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![Residuals vs. fitted for three specifications. The log-log model is closest to the ideal flat smoother.](demo_files/figure-html/fig-resid-compare-1.png){#fig-resid-compare width=1056}
:::
:::


The log-log model is clearly best. We adopt it as our working model.

## The RESET test: a formal functional form check


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
resettest(model_ext)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```

	RESET test

data:  model_ext
RESET = 386.33, df1 = 2, df2 = 9643, p-value < 2.2e-16
```


:::

```{.r .cell-code}
resettest(model_work)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```

	RESET test

data:  model_work
RESET = 156.44, df1 = 2, df2 = 9643, p-value < 2.2e-16
```


:::
:::


The level-level model fails badly (p ≪ 0.05); the log-log model still rejects but the test statistic is much smaller. Note: rejection tells you *something* is wrong, not *what* to change — the residual plot guides the fix.

::: {.callout-tip}
A useful workflow: RESET first to flag a problem, residual plot to diagnose it, revised model to fix it.
:::

---

# Heteroskedasticity

## Building the scale-location plot

The scale-location plot shows $\sqrt{|\text{standardised residuals}|}$ on the y-axis. If variance is constant, this band should be flat. Again we build it manually from `augment()`:


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
augment(model_work) |>
  ggplot(aes(.fitted, sqrt(abs(.std.resid)))) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.12, color = "steelblue", size = 0.7) +
  geom_smooth(method = "loess", se = FALSE, color = "tomato", linewidth = 1) +
  labs(
    x = "Fitted values (log scale)",
    y = "√|Standardised residuals|",
    title = "Scale-location: log(price) ~ log(distance) + stars",
    subtitle = "A flat horizontal smoother = homoskedastic"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![Scale-location plot: the upward slope reveals heteroskedasticity in the log-log model.](demo_files/figure-html/fig-scaleloc-manual-1.png){#fig-scaleloc-manual width=672}
:::
:::


The smoother rises toward higher fitted values — hotels in expensive cities show more price dispersion than the model can absorb. OLS estimates are still unbiased, but standard errors are unreliable.

## The Breusch-Pagan test


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
bptest(model_work)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```

	studentized Breusch-Pagan test

data:  model_work
BP = 192.96, df = 2, p-value < 2.2e-16
```


:::
:::


Null: homoskedasticity. The tiny p-value formalises what the plot showed. We reject.

## Robust standard errors

The fix is to replace the classical standard errors with heteroskedasticity-consistent (HC) ones. The estimates do not change — only the expressed uncertainty.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
# Direct output
coeftest(model_work, vcov = vcovHC(model_work, type = "HC1"))
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```

t test of coefficients:

                      Estimate Std. Error t value  Pr(>|t|)    
(Intercept)          3.7599122  0.0258337 145.543 < 2.2e-16 ***
log(distance + 0.1) -0.0404109  0.0064885  -6.228  4.92e-10 ***
stars                0.3150797  0.0073421  42.914 < 2.2e-16 ***
---
Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
```


:::
:::


For reporting, compare both in a single table:


::: {#tbl-robust .cell tbl-cap='Classical vs. HC1 robust SEs. Estimates identical; inference differs.'}

```{.r .cell-code}
modelsummary(
  list("Classical SEs" = model_work, "HC1 robust SEs" = model_work),
  vcov        = list("classical", "HC1"),
  stars       = TRUE,
  gof_omit    = "AIC|BIC|Log|F|RMSE",
  coef_rename = c("log(distance + 0.1)" = "log(distance)", "stars" = "Stars")
)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}

