# Normality of Residuals

## Building the Q-Q plot


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
hotels_aug |>
  ggplot(aes(sample = .std.resid)) +
  stat_qq(alpha = 0.15, color = "steelblue", size = 0.7) +
  stat_qq_line(color = "tomato", linewidth = 1) +
  labs(
    x     = "Theoretical normal quantiles",
    y     = "Sample quantiles of std. residuals",
    title = "Q-Q plot of standardised residuals"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![Q-Q plot: standardised residuals vs. theoretical normal quantiles. Near-diagonal points = approximately normal residuals.](demo_files/figure-html/fig-qq-manual-1.png){#fig-qq-manual width=672}
:::
:::


The tails deviate slightly from the diagonal — heavier than a perfect normal. With $n = 9{,}648$, the Central Limit Theorem ensures this does not affect our inference.

## The Shapiro-Wilk trap


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
set.seed(42)
shapiro.test(sample(resid(model_work), 5000))
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```

	Shapiro-Wilk normality test

data:  sample(resid(model_work), 5000)
W = 0.99035, p-value < 2.2e-16
```


:::
:::


p ≪ 0.001. With nearly 10,000 observations, Shapiro-Wilk has enough power to detect trivially small departures from normality. This result does not indicate a practical problem.

